{
  "answer": "**In \"Saqaliya\" (Chapter 21 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*), Allama Iqbal voices a poignant lament for the \"grave of Hejazi civilization\" in Sicily—the lost glory of early Islamic/Arab rule there (roughly 9th–11th centuries CE), once marked by seafaring prowess, imperial conquests, and cultural renewal, now reduced to ruins.[^1][^2][^3]**\n\n**He parallels this with famous historical laments: Hafez (the \"nightingale of Shiraz\") for sacked Baghdad (1258), Dagh for ruined Delhi/Jahanabad (post-1857), and Ibn Badrun for fallen Granada (1492).[^4] Iqbal positions himself as the destined poet to mourn Sicily's concealed story of pain and faded splendor.[^5]**\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Saqaliya\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-13e58a,p-ac137c,p-c707f9,p-ab88c0).\n\n[^3]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Ch. 21, [full chapter](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, \"Saqaliya\" [paragraph](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-02c3ef).\n\n[^5]: Ibid., [paragraphs](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-efa635,p-3ff1f9,p-a060f8).",
